commentBody:
@Dean

Yes!

I happened to look down and notice that landmine.  My gut said Z.  By the time I got to the end, I would have never remembered to go back and check that one.

@Charles Peterson

Is there a song by Sondheim called "Tonight"?

When I read CLM's lyrics, I could hear Bernstein's Tonight in me head.

@Francis
Mr. Bernstein wrote the music. Mr. Sondheim wrote the lyrics.
Or, as the famous anecdote would have put it: "Sondheim wrote, 'Tonight, tonight...' Bernstein wrote, 'La-LA, la-LA...'"

@Francis

I eyed that for quite a while, thinking, "This can't be right!" before I put the "e" in. 

The music played and still I pondered a bit, then reread the clue. Ooooooooooh, ok.

@Lige
@CatPaws

I think PRAGENCY might be the DOOKiest of all DOOKs.

Those of you who monitor these things:  do we have a dook-o-meter reading on pragency?

@Cindy

Thank you!
See you there!

@sotto voce

As always, you’re too kind. He’s just here for the marathon and to pay homage to Steve “Pre.”  (IYKYN, as they say.) Since we’re retired, we follow him to his marathons like his own personal deadheads. Seeing some fun cities. Just got back from walking around Eugene & U of O. Apparently, it’s spring football game Saturday (Penn State calls it the Blue-White game). A glorified scrimmage game, but with all the undergraduate partying. (A helpful student explained to us what these gallon jug B.O.R.G.s are.)

Yeah, I’ve been limiting my posts, but still reading and rec-ing. And if you’re ever near upstate NY, let us know (<a href="mailto:wembosox04@gmail.com">wembosox04@gmail.com</a>)! Our next trip out this way is for daughter’s “planned elopement” in Hawaii this fall. (Yes, as the clergyman in the Princess Bride might say, she’s getting Maui-ed.)

@Times Rita
Which just goes to show what a brilliant marketer Ego Tusk is. 
It reminds me of the Simpsons episode  where Maggie is sent to the Ayn Rand Daycare. (I understand that the Musketeer is a serious student of Rand.) The walls are decorated with posters bearing, in Brutalist capitals, cheerful messages such as "A is A." Never too soon to suppress all hope, whimsy, joy, and desire. Step on it! Crush it!

@Elbridge Gerry

Billie said that they aren’t MICE. They are. For the purposes of judging whether the clue is fine, that’s enough. 

Yes, that other word is in the dictionary, but it’s still an atrocity.

@Steph
I occasionally use the NYT Games app. I'm not aware of a NYT Wordplay app.
From within the NYT Games app, the link to this ever-popular forum launches my browser. I don't see how accessing this wonderful column can be otherwise.

@Jane Wheelaghan
Way back in the day, here in the US there was (and maybe still is) a Seeing Eye Foundation. The German Shepard pups were raised  by members of the 4H clubs of America. Once the pups reached adulthood, they underwent months of  training by professionals, and the graduates were called Seeing Eye Dogs.

Today, they are mostly referred to as guide dogs, but there are also service dogs and comfort dogs, who serve other functions outside of guiding the blind.

@Paul Turner

In a city I knew in California, a "flat" referred to an apartment that was remodeled as part of a one-family house--like today's additional dwelling units (ADU). 

This distinguished it from an "apartment" that was part of an apartment building built as apartments.

@Anonymous

At one time and in one way or level or to one extent or another, we are all "we."

No?

@Xword Junkie

You beat me by a good margin.
IOMOTH was new to me, I think; I'll try to remember it in the future.

@Marcia Fidler 
@Tony

All the little birdies go
TWEET, TWEET, TWEET.  

Rockin Robin is in my head.

@Tony
With all due respect to the Birdie fans, West Side Story is clearly the superior work in every aspect: libretto, music, lyrics. Just no comparison.
Sadly, I concede that earworminess is unrelated to artistic merit. Just think of all those annoying jingles that clog up perfectly usable brain spsce.

@Rich in Atlanta
Hi
I replied to you post yesterday about our dads being in the RAF but it didn't appear - so I amended it - but it still didn't appear! So I won't refer to its contents in case it happens again ..... but salute to both our fighting fathers.

@Michael B.

There are SO many insects with distracting/off-putting "false eye-spots" that I was flummoxed for a little while.  Then I got 6D (we buy HEPA filters by the dozen in the Land of Pollen) and was sure it was a MOTH....and how many MOTHs have a two-letter name?  

My whole solve was kind of like that...I had to creep up on the elusive answer little by little.....

@Andrzej

Wow if you completed this without lookups when English isn’t your first language I bow to you, you are a stud.
By the way wanted to thank you for your “Tainted Grail” video game recommendation. I’m enjoying it. A bit quirky and had a steep difficulty slope to start, but it’s smooth sailing now and it’s holding my interest longer than many of the same genre.

@SP

Oh, wow, cool! That's great to hear. It's a bit iffy technically, but other than that I found it to be one of the most enjoyable games I have ever played - and it was made by a Polish indie developer, which makes mme feel proud even though I had nothing to do with it.

My ranger struggled a bit in the beginning, too, but she grew greatly it power as she progressed.

@Andrzej

Yes when I feel like it’s a slog rather than fun I give up too. Couldn’t get far in Elden Ring for that reason.
In Tainted Grail I went with a stealth archer, which was also slow going until I discovered summoning as a backup which pretty much covers all situations. Wyra thanks for the suggestion.

